40":"about 1040","1018":"1018","1139":"1139","1117":"1117","1039":"1039","1036":"1036","1046":"1046","1068":"1068","1034":"1034","about 1068":"about 1068","1109":"1109","Château-Landon, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France":"Château-Landon, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France","Montlhery, Seine-Et-Oise, France":"Montlhéry, Seine-et-Oise, France","Courtenay, Loiret, Centre, France":"Courtenay, Loiret, Centre-Val de Loire, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hildegarde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an old Germanic female personal name composed of <i>hild</i> ‘battle’ + <i>gard</i> ‘enclosure’. It was borne by the second wife of Charlemagne and by the mystical writer  Hildegard  of Bingen (  1098–1179 ), in whose music and writings there has been great interest in recent decades."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hildegarde de Gâtinais was born about 1040, in Château-Landon, Seine-et-Marne, Île-de-France, France, her father, Geoffroy II 'Ferréol' de Gâstinais, was 41 and her mother, Ermengarde dite Blanche d'Anjou, was 23. She married Joscelin de Courtenay seigneur de Courtenay in 1055, in Montlhéry, Seine-et-Oise, France. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died about 1068, 